// For high volume situations, it may be necessary to utilize a disconnected, or stateless session. In this context, a session is not managed by the client, but a pool of sessions are managed in the server. The lifecycle of a session pool goes as follows.

// The first request using disconnected mode comes into the server. The server connects the minimum number of sessions configured in the web.config.

// Every subsequent request comes in and consumes a different session in the pool.

// If the minimum number of sessions are in use when a request comes in, new sessions will be connected for each request until the maximum number of sessions is connected.

// Once the maximum number of sessions are all in use, a request will wait for a session to be released back to the pool before consuming it and doing its work.

// It might take some trial and error to set the correct minimum and maximum number of sessions. The default is 0 minimum and 10 maximum.

//   Caution

// There are a number of overloads on the Connect method that were deprecated in OnBase 11, it is highly recommended to use the overload Connect(AuthenticationProperties).

